    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-16T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-16T09:00:00-05:00" n="514"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d514">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.00/570: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-16T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 16, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 17—9:31 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. British Ambassador’s recommendations as reported in my 75,<note n="32"
                        xml:id="d514fn32">Dated April 11, 10 p.m., <ref target="#pg_499">p.
                            499</ref>.</note> have been approved by Cabinet and he will see Gailani
                    today. This might result in peaceful landing British troops especially in view
                    strength of accompanying naval units.</p>
                <p>It is possible my telegrams are not being sent and I therefore asked Ambassador
                    to request Foreign Office, London, to keep our Embassy informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
